pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 657317351, 'comment_body': 'Should rather be `if not dir:`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 17, 29, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657325197, 'comment_body': 'I think this should be done for slope, shear force, and bending moment also. Better to directly use the helper functions of the individual plotting functions (`_plot_slope() ..etc`)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 17, 38, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657976888, 'comment_body': "I did it for deflection only because deflection covers all the variables needed for calculating slope, bending moment, and shear force. If deflection is determinable, we can definitely determine other equations as the code works in order.

I didn't use the helper functions because I wanted to impart different colors to different functions. Using helper functions will plot all the x graphs as red, y as blue, etc unless we modify the helper functions to take color as a parameter.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 14, 2, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Psycho-Pirate', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659275503, 'comment_body': "I think the idea is to have different line colors within a single plot. So you can change the color of the helper functions in a way that when you use them here all the line colors in this plot are different. (I won't recommend using color as a parameter)

", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 27, 7, 13, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659276065, 'comment_body': "> ....because deflection covers all the variables needed for calculating slope, bending moment, and shear force

IMO there can be a use case where this won't hold true. Or is this something proven?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 27, 7, 18, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659300278, 'comment_body': "> IMO there can be a use case where this won't hold true. Or is this something proven?

The functions are calculated by integrating the lower functions starting from the load. Shear Force is calculated by integrating load, Bending Moment is calculated by integrating shear force, and so on. Deflection is the function at the top so it covers everything below it and adds on some additional variables. Hence it contains all the variables needed for all the other functions. If Deflection can be calculated, it can be proven that other functions have already been calculated and the variables they contain are already present. 

Even in beam2d class, only Deflection is used for ```plot_loading_results()``` because of the same reason. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 27, 10, 38, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Psycho-Pirate', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: [GSoC] Function for I.L.D. for reaction loads added
pr_body:
#### References to other Issues or PRs
<!-- If this pull request fixes an issue, write "Fixes #NNNN" in that exact
format, e.g. "Fixes #1234" (see
https://tinyurl.com/auto-closing for more information). Also, please
write a comment on that issue linking back to this pull request once it is
open. -->
See #19069

#### Brief description of what is fixed or changed
Function `solve_for_ild_reactions()` is added which returns the reaction equations under the effect of a moving load.
Function `plot_ild_reactions()` is added which plots these equations.

#### Other comments


#### Release Notes

<!-- Write the release notes for this release below. See
https://github.com/sympy/sympy/wiki/Writing-Release-Notes for more information
on how to write release notes. The bot will check your release notes
automatically to see if they are formatted correctly. -->

<!-- BEGIN RELEASE NOTES -->
* physics.continuum_mechanics 
   * Added ability to calculate and plot I.L.D. Reaction Equations
<!-- END RELEASE NOTES -->
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 667294474, 'comment_body': 'What is the purpose of this `X` when we have `self.variable`?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 10, 5, 40, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 667299431, 'comment_body': "In order to solve the slope and moment equations, a limit (lim x->L) is applied. Here 'x' represents the length of the beam. The uppercase 'X' represents the distance of the moving load from origin. I have also explained this in my gsoc proposal.
![Screenshot (6)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/50932406/125154115-08811580-e176-11eb-828f-9d8a13c4e216.png)
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 10, 6, 32, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Psycho-Pirate', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 667305975, 'comment_body': 'Firstly the big `X` is something the user never defined and thus would never know what it is. So you might have to provide user information about this `X` or create a similar flow of how the small `x` is taken as a parameter when a Beam object is defined.

Secondly, according to what I understand, `x` and `X` both vary over the beam length, and represent any random cross-section over the length, so we can use the same variable for them, unless there is some issue in solving the equations.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 10, 7, 42, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 667331067, 'comment_body': "> Secondly, according to what I understand, `x` and `X` both vary over the beam length, and represent any random cross-section over the length, so we can use the same variable for them, unless there is some issue in solving the equations.

The only reason I added 'X' was to avoid confusion as X is not any distance on the beam, it is the distance at which the moving load is acting. But if it causes more confusion then it can be definitely removed.
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 10, 12, 2, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Psycho-Pirate', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 671640266, 'comment_body': 'Variable name should be something more relevant for code readability', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 17, 7, 56, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 671640477, 'comment_body': 'Here too, it can be `for reaction, equation in self._ild_reactions` or something better than just `i`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 17, 7, 59, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 671640811, 'comment_body': 'A property can also be defined for the same for the user to access', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 17, 8, 2, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 671644094, 'comment_body': 'Why a keyerror? I think it should be a ValueError instead. Also, the message should be elaborated like: "I.L.D. reaction equations not found. Please use `solve_for_ild_reactions()` to generate the I.L.D. reaction equations"', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 17, 8, 35, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 680490481, 'comment_body': "`solve_for_ild_reactions` probably shouldn't return anything, it should just update the value of `self._ild_reactions`.
It goes with the behavior of the other solve functions in the module.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 1, 10, 37, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 680503576, 'comment_body': 'This line is not required anymore then.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 1, 12, 23, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ishanaj', 'type': 'User'}]
